ing=1><tr><td valign=top bgcolor=#666eb0 class=headings><font color=#FFFFFF>Author</font></td><td valign=top bgcolor=#666eb0 class=headings><font color=#FFFFFF>Comment</font></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=riverdane>Riverdane</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 409<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(7/16/03 2:04 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=55.topic&index=41>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Wake (Mithaniel's Handmaiden, Breathe III)</span><hr size=1> The horns announcing her presence had no sooner finished blowing when she dropped to one knee, staring at the floor at Mithaniel’s feet, unable and unwilling to raise her eyes to meet his.  Terris she was able to look upon directly, but here, in the presence of her god, the God of Honor, she trembled in awe and steadied to keep from falling face first supplicant before him.<br>
<br>
“Camille Wyldechylde.”, he said, voice coming down from high above her, rich and full of vibrancy, steady and clear.<br>
<br>
“My Lord.”, she said, looking upon his massive boots.  “It is my honor that You know who I am.”<br>
<br>
“No, my child,” he said after a pause, “It is mine, and my shame.”<br>
<br>
“Shame, My Lord?” Camille dared ask.<br>
<br>
“You know I have stood near you similar to this before?” he asked.<br>
<br>
“Aye, I do, my Lord.”, she replied.  “During End Game.  My husband told me.”<br>
<br>
“And yet you still worship me?” Mithaniel asked, slightly surprised.  “Knowing the last time we were this close I had come to snuff out your life?”<br>
<br>
“You were doing as You saw right for the greater good.”, was her reply.<br>
<br>
“The greater good,” Mithaniel said ironically.  “The greater good would have been the end of us all, if your husband had not interceded on your behalf.”<br>
<br>
“While others stood paralyzed with fear for their own existences, You acted on the behalf of others.” Camille rejoined.  “Your only error, if I may be so bold to suggest there had been any at all, would have been a misinterpretation of the intelligence afforded You.”<br>
<br>
“How delicately put.” Mithaniel said, laughing suddenly.   “I know why you have come.  I heard your prayer.  My eyes have always turned to you when my name is uttered by your lips, since End Game.”<br>
<br>
“Will You help, my Lord?” Camille asked.<br>
<br>
“I will provide you with the quest for the sword, yes.” Mithaniel said.<br>
<br>
“It is all I could ask of You.”, she said, although a part of her wanted to scream JUST GIVE ME THE SWORD! <br>
<br>
“You wonder why I do not give you the weapon whole.”, he stated, seeming to read her mind, which most likely, he had done.<br>
<br>
“Yes, my Lord.”, she answered honestly.<br>
<br>
“I am the God of Honor.”, he replied.  “And even as the end of two worlds draw near, what will the bards say of the woman who was handed her foe in chains, head stretched across the block, as she brought her sword upon his neck to save them?  She would be no hero in my eyes; she would be an executioner.  No, I will give you the quest, and if you are indeed worthy, you will complete it, and with its reward attempt to save your worlds.  You will go forth with Honor, and succeed or fail, know when it is all done you were true to your calling, and true to your God.”<br>
<br>
“Yes, my Lord.” Camille said, knowing deep inside herself he was right, but full of self doubt at her ability to do something this important, with the lives of two worlds hanging in the balance.  Or maybe it was the fact that she was gambling with the only thing left of her husband.  Her mind was so awash with questions and fears that little made sense.<br>
<br>
“Earthcarver.” Mithaniel mused.  “Only one other paladin had ever inquired after that sword.  Ex-paladin I should say.  His desire for it was a petty foul reason, but I did not think to question his motives, since he had served me so diligently in the past.  I did not think to examine his soul, as I have done yours, and see what hides beyond the knelt knee and promise to serve.  You may cross paths with this anti-paladin while performing your quest, for he still seeks Earthcarver.  When he finishes his quest, he intends to use it to behead a statue of me that stands in the temple in North Freeport, when he and that foul Freeport Militia he runs overthrow the paladins there.  Lucan D’lere always was a child, even when he grew out of his knickers and into the armor of a man.”<br>
<br>
Camille started involuntarily, eyes still fixed to the floor.  Lucan D’lere!  After all those years.  She hoped feverently that her path may not cross that of her old suitor.  If she never laid eyes upon him again except as the guest of honor in a funeral march, she would be content.<br>
<br>
“The Quest:” Mithaniel intoned.  “The hilt and pommel are already crafted, and are the handle for a great many ancient quested sword, serving both good and evil alike.  The blade is what determines the alignment for the sword.  The hilt and pommel lay deep in the Castle Mistmoore, clasped in the hands of Mistmoore himself.  They must be acquired.  He sleeps with it, knowing that it serves as the base of yet another blade, that may one day be used to remove him from your world.  This is the first stage of your quest, recover the hilt and pommel from him.<br>
<br>
The blade itself must be crafted from ore that has undergone a transformation; platinum and gold tempered in dragon-breath.  There are extremely limited sources for these metals.  You need to find ten coins weight each, to be mixed with common steel.  The gold can be found in the lair of Lord Nagafen, from his bed.  As he sleeps upon a pile of gold, his foul exhale over countless years has created the metal that you need; recognize it as the gold coins with their insignias melted from their faces.  Years of hoarding should have a goodly pile for you to sift through.  The platinum is in the lair of Lady Vox, likewise, simple platinum coins bearing no mark but a smooth finish.  Take this ore to a master blacksmith, and have the blacksmith forge the blade and create your sword.”<br>
<br>
“My Lord.”  Camille pointed out hesitantly.  “It is said of dragons lairs that when they are occupied by the dragon, people trained to the degree that I have been are unable to enter without being banished instantly…”<br>
<br>
“And is still the case.” Mithaniel replied.  “Find a way, Camille Wyldechylde.”<br>
<br>
“Yes, my Lord.” Camille answered, sighing inwardly at the apparent impossibility of her task.  “There is one other thing…”<br>
<br>
“Passage to Luclin.”, he said, again, anticipating her question.  “Your friend the gnome was on the right track, you will go upon a steed similar to River’s mount.  Seek the Mother of All, and tell Her I have sent you.  Tunare will know what to do.”<br>
<br>
“I shall, my Lord.” Camille said, still staring at his boots.  “And my humble thanks.”<br>
<br>
“Succeed or fail, Camille Wyldechylde, but go with honor.” Mithaniel commanded.  “I shall send you to the gates of Freeport to put your house in order and begin.  And the next time I see you, may it be standing victorious before me, not as a suit of empty armor in my halls.”<br>
<br>
Camille knelt silently.  There was nothing more to be said.<br>
<br>
And, upon blinking, she opened her eyes and saw not his brilliant boots, but the dirt of West Freeport.  Climbing to her feet and lifting her eyes to the dawn that had found the city, she entered the town. <br>
 <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.lby3.com/eq/leopa/misc/riverdane_animatedbanner.gif" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=riverdane>Riverdane</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 411<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(7/17/03 12:30 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=55.topic&index=42>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Wake (Mithaniel's Handmaiden, Breathe III)</span><hr size=1> The door was opened after the second knock by a woman in her early 50’s.  Her blonde hair had liberal dash of gray throughout.  But what the years had done to her hair, it could not do to her face.  It was still beautiful.  The woman carried a cup of coffee in her hand and blinked in surprise in the morning light.<br>
<br>
“Camille?” she asked.<br>
<br>
“Good morning, mom.”  Camille said.<br>
<br>
Emaus Spelldancer swung the door wide, ushering in the daughter she had not seen in eight months with a wide smile.  “Come in, come in!” she exclaimed.  “Your father is still asleep, but I’ll wake him.  He’ll be so happy to see you!”<br>
<br>
“Let daddy sleep for now…” Camille tried, but her mother would not hear it.<br>
<br>
“Nonsense!” she hushed her.  “If he finds out I let him sleep through a visit from you, he’ll sic his pet on me.  There’s some coffee on the stove.  Pour your father’s and grab yourself a cup.”<br>
<br>
“Thanks, mom.” Camille said.  Sleeping till sunset the day before or not, the night had worn her down.  Camille went into the kitchen and prepared two cups of coffee.<br>
<br>
“Sylver, get up.” she heard her mother say.  Then something muttered in return.  “Get up, or I’ll tell Camille you were too tired to see her!”<br>
<br>
“Camille?” she heard her father say, awake in an instant.  “She’s here??”<br>
<br>
“She’s in the kitchen.” she heard Emaus say happily, then,  “Don’t go out like that!  Put on some clothes before you scare her off!”<br>
<br>
“Heh, aye.” he said, “Hand me that robe, would you please?”<br>
<br>
Camille stirred her coffee and waited.<br>
<br>
Sylver Spelldancer came into the room with arms open, a ridiculous grin on his aging face.  Time had not been as kind to the old mage as it had to his wife.  “As it should be!” he had been known to say, “My hair finally matches my name, I only feel sorry for ‘Maus that I didn’t turn out as pretty as she did!”.  <br>
<br>
Camille stood up and let her father hug her, kissing his bearded cheek lightly and returning the embrace.<br>
<br>
“Easy, oh knight!” he exclaimed.  “With all that armor you’re not as soft as you used to be!”<br>
<br>
Camille handed him his coffee.  “Two sugars still, daddy?”<br>
<br>
“Aye,” he said, “Sweet like your mother.”<br>
<br>
Emaus blushed prettily.  Camille, even bearing the weight of the last few days, could not help but smile.  After all these years they were still doing the same old corny routines.  As a teen it had embarrassed her, but now, after all this, well…they still had what she wished she did.  They were together.  And she would have made herself a fool for love in front of all of Antonica if it would bring her man back from his cold sleep.  But he was gone, soul locked away by a madman, with the intention of draining every last bit of ….<br>
<br>
“Honey?” Emaus said, looking at her with concern.  “Is something wrong?”<br>
<br>
Camille realized suddenly that she was on the verge of crying, eyes brimming with tears.  She stood hastily. <br>
<br>
“No, it’s just…” she tried, and lost the words, arms dangling uselessly at her sides, as she fought the tears.<br>
<br>
“Camille, what’s wrong?” her father asked in alarm.  But she couldn’t bring herself to speak.<br>
<br>
And then her mother was on her feet and opening her arms to her, and she fell into them, burying her head into Emaus’ shoulder.<br>
<br>
What now, she could hear River say, Knights don’t cry.<br>
<br>
Yes they do River, she thought incoherently to herself.  Sometimes they do.<br>
<br>
And hugging her mother close to her, she openly wept.<br>
 <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.lby3.com/eq/leopa/misc/riverdane_animatedbanner.gif" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=riverdane>Riverdane</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 412<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(7/17/03 12:33 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=55.topic&index=43>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Wake (Mithaniel's Handmaiden, Breathe III)</span><hr size=1> She had cried herself dry, while her mother stroked her hair absently, not saying a word.  Afterwards, Camille sat back down, wiping her eyes.  Sylver shifted uncomfortably in his seat, not quite knowing what to say.<br>
<br>
“It’s alright to cry.” Emaus said, seating herself.  “If I ever lost your father, I would be crying forever.”<br>
<br>
“It’s not just that,” Camille said, picking up her coffee again with shaking hands.  “Losing River was bad enough, but…”  She paused, unsure of how much to tell them.  Sylver gave her a look to go on, sensing she had more to say.  <br>
<br>
So she told them everything.<br>
<br>
When she had finished, she sat back in the chair, exhausted.  Emaus’ face had drained of all color.  And Sylver’s hands were clenched on the table’s edge.  He was furious.<br>
<br>
“THIS is why I never chose a god!” he exploded.  “Sending you off on a quest to Mistmoore!  And against dragons!  With what, a guarantee you’ll come back safely?  No, just a good luck!”<br>
<br>
“Daddy,” Camille began, “It’s about honor…”<br>
<br>
“I don’t give a rat’s ass about honor!”  Sylver thundered, beside himself.  “He is marching you into possible death while he sits fat in his plane watching like a crowd at the arena!  And Whizbang, if I could get my hands on him, I’d wring his scrawny neck, sending MY little girl out to get herself killed…”<br>
<br>
“Daddy, it is my responsibility…” Camille tried.<br>
<br>
“WHAT responsibility?” Sylver cried.  “It was bad enough that husband of yours had you crawling around every stinking pit in Norrath treasure seeking!  Now even in death he has to drag you down with him?!”<br>
<br>
“Sylver!” Emaus reprimanded him, shock in her voice.  Camille’s mouth dropped open as she stared at her father.<br>
<br>
“Don’t contradict me again, ‘Maus!”  Sylver warned.  “Not this time!  When she wanted to play tin soldier and I didn’t approve, you talked me into it.  Then when River started showing up at the door and I didn’t like it, you interfered there.  I warned you both about him, and now look!  Widowed before she is thirty five, no children, and running head first after River again into danger.  His lifestyle KILLED him, Camille, and it will kill you too!”<br>
<br>
“I don’t believe you are saying this to me…” Camille said numbly, cheeks growing hot.<br>
<br>
“Nor do I.” Emaus said angrily.  “When Dane died River looked to you as a father, and was a good son-in-law, to both of us.  I thought you cared for the man.  You wept after River’s funeral.  Where is all this coming from, Sylver??”<br>
<br>
“River is DEAD.” Sylver retorted, standing.  “Must he take my little girl away again?” He was shaking in rage.<br>
<br>
“I am not your little girl anymore!” Camille nearly screamed.  And then, pushing past him, tears once again in her eyes, she ran blindly through the house, automatically running for her old familiar bedroom.  Slamming the door behind her, she fell onto the bed, still decorated the same way she had left it twelve years before, and cried hot angry tears.  Exhaustion, adrenaline, and the unexpected harsh words from her father made all of the strength go out of her.  She stopped crying and just lay with her head in the pillow, unable to lift it.  She dimly heard her parents arguing in hushed tones from the kitchen.<br>
<br>
“You old fool, what’s gotten into you?” Emaus furiously said to her husband.<br>
<br>
“How can they do that to her?”  Sylver shot back.  “How can they put the pressure of saving two worlds on her shoulders?”<br>
<br>
“How can they do this to her?” Emaus replied with a snort of disdain.  “How can YOU do this to her?  And to speak of River that way!  You didn’t mean half of what you said, yet all you managed to do is hurt the very daughter you think you are protecting!”<br>
<br>
“I had to make her see, ‘Maus…” Sylver said desperately.<br>
<br>
“All you have done is alienate her.” Emaus went on unsympathetically.  “After a year of mourning she finally comes home to us…”<br>
<br>
“To say goodbye!” Sylver cried.<br>
<br>
“To say goodbye, so what?” Emaus yelled back.  “Would you have preferred she didn’t come at all?”<br>
<br>
“No, of course not!” he retorted, shocked by the accusation.  And then, all of the anger was out of his voice, and he just sounded…old.  “What if she gets hurt, ‘Maus?   What if she dies?”<br>
<br>
“If she dies, we all die.” Emaus said gently, so quietly that Camille in her exhaustion could barely make it out.  “If it were you, you in that gem, do you think you could have prevented me from going after you?”<br>
<br>
“I wouldn’t be able to stop you.” Sylver said softly.  “You would have ice-cometed anyone who got in your way.”<br>
<br>
“Then let her do what she has to do.” Emaus suggested calmly.<br>
<br>
“She is a girl…” Sylver argued weakly.<br>
<br>
“She is a woman.” Emaus corrected him.  “And that is her man.”<br>
<br>
And then Camille heard nothing more, as she fell finally into a deep sleep.<br>
 <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.lby3.com/eq/leopa/misc/riverdane_animatedbanner.gif" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=riverdane>Riverdane</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 412<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(7/17/03 12:36 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=55.topic&index=44>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Wake (Mithaniel's Handmaiden, Breathe III)</span><hr size=1> “Why are you asking me about shadowknights?”  Sylver asked her, eyebrow raised, when she pressed him for an answer a third time.  The first question from his not quite twenty year old daughter came out of the blue: Are shadowknights bad?  Yes, he said, now, have you decided on a last name or are you hopefully staying with Spelldancer?  Can humans be shadowknights? she asked instead.  Rare, but yes, he said, did you decide who you are taking to the Graduation Ball?  Can a shadowknight be good? came her third question, to which he finally grew concerned with her line of questioning.<br>
<br>
“Why?” she said.  “Well, I met one the other day…”<br>
<br>
“You what?” he said, face clouding.  “Is this what this Knights of Truth is going to be about?  I was as proud as your mother when your information from that North Ro thing uncovered that ambush on the Oasis caravan,  but if your line of work is going to involve you with shadowknights…”<br>
<br>
“Daddy,” Camille sigh with exasperation, “Do you recall the man whom I said helped me when I was captured?”<br>
<br>
“Dane’s son, aye.” Sylver said, “Don’t change the subject miss.  I haven’t forgotten, I will be heading to Dane’s house to thank his boy personally later today.  Now, where did you meet this shadowknight?  Did he attack you?”<br>
<br>
“He saved me.” she retorted.  “Riverdane is a shadowknight.”<br>
<br>
The look of surprise on Sylver’s face was a guilty reward for Camille.  “A what?”<br>
<br>
“A shadowknight.” Camille said.  “He tried to train as a paladin, but the teaching wouldn’t take.”<br>
<br>
“A shadowknight.” Sylver repeated quietly.  “Of course the son of crazy Eleese would be something odd like that.”<br>
<br>
“You know who his mother is?” Camille said.<br>
<br>
“Every adult in the town knew when Dane brought her into Freeport.  The ignorant of the city had a story she was touched by Innoruuk.  A crazy notion, but it spread.  I didn’t put much stock into the story, despite how wild-eyed and jumpy as she was when he brought her back to the city when he first found her.  She cleaned up well enough after leaving the woods.  But when she grew pregnant and went into labor, the midwives would not attend to her.  She died in Kithicor.  Dane was trying to bring her to Rivervale for help delivering the child.”<br>
<br>
“That is horrible.” Camille said, her young senses affronted.<br>
<br>
“That is human nature.” Sylver said.  “It is ignorance.  What we don’t understand, we fear.  What we fear, we kill or let die.  Then there is nothing to fear.”<br>
<br>
“Daddy,” Camille said playfully, her eyes softening the irony of her next statement.  “Do you understand Riverdane?”<br>
<br>
“Bah!” he cried, seeing how neat a trap she had led him into.  “I appreciate that he saved your life, but I understand shadowknights.  Maybe his human nature is different, but why would he choose to go down the road of evil?  For that’s what they are, Camille, evil.  How could Dane stand to have him practice that dark art in his home? I’m amazed, but then again look at his wife.  Dane never walked the easy road.”<br>
<br>
“River is not evil.” Camille said, folding her arms across her chest.  <br>
<br>
“How are you so sure about this boy?” Sylver retorted, folding his as well.  Camille looked like her mother, with none of Sylver’s homely looks and graying brown hair, but at the moment, striking the same pose, no one would have ever guessed incorrectly whether they were father and daughter.  Emaus walked into the scene at that moment, and uttered a short laugh.<br>
<br>
“Fine fine, if neither of you will take out the garbage, I’LL do it.” she said.<br>
<br>
“Let the pet.”  Sylver said, whistling.  An air elemental entered the room, turning invisible as it did.  The garbage lifted as if by magic and floated out of the room.<br>
<br>
“So much better than the earth elemental.” Emaus nodded approvingly.  “That thing left more tracks on the floor than it was worth.  So, what are you two disagreeing about now?”<br>
<br>
“Your daughter is bringing home a troll!” Sylver exclaimed, mock-serious.<br>
<br>
“Daddy!” Camille shrieked, lightly bonking him on the head.  “I’m not bringing home a troll!  I’m not bringing home Riverdane either!  I’m just asking!”<br>
<br>
“Why is Riverdane a troll?” Emaus asked, confused.<br>
<br>
“He is a shadowknight.” Sylver said.<br>
<br>
“Really?” Eamus said, eyes dancing.  “How exciting!”<br>
<br>
“Don’t you encourage this!” Sylver pleaded, realizing he was outnumbered as his wife beamed at him.<br>
<br>
“Encourage what?” Emaus asked innocently.  “I just think that’s rather exciting, don’t you, Camille?”<br>
<br>
“It is rather odd.” Camille agreed.<br>
<br>
“Why oh why did I marry a wizard?” Sylver sighed, throwing up his hands.  “Anyone who spends their free time blowing things up cannot be sensible at all.”<br>
<br>
“You married me, Sylver,” Emaus began, pulling Sylver close in a loose embrace, beginning one of their timeless routines, “because you didn’t have…”<br>
<br>
“…a horse, I know.” Sylver finished for her, as usual.<br>
<br>
Emaus sighed and rolled her eyes at her daughter.  “I’m nothing to your father except a port bish.”<br>
<br>
“Mother!” Camille laughed in shock.<br>
<br>
“But you’re MY port bish.” Sylver replied, kissing her quickly on the lips.<br>
<br>
“Daddy!” Camille exclaimed.  She could not believe this conversation.<br>
<br>
Camille stood looking at them holding each other, and suddenly sighed.<br>
<br>
“What’s wrong, Cami?” her mother asked, releasing Sylver.<br>
<br>
“Nothing.”  she said.  “I’m just looking at you two so happy and wondering who I am going to bring to the Graduation Ball.”<br>
<br>
“Lucan won’t bring you?” Sylver asked, surprised.<br>
<br>
“Oh, Lucan would bring me alright.” Camille said bitterly.  “It’s more a question of do I want to be his trophy date or not.  And the answer is more no than yes, Daddy.”<br>
<br>
“Ah, I see.” Sylver said, frowning.<br>
<br>
“I want a man like you found.” Camille said earnestly to her mother, making Sylver blush uncomfortably.  “I want him to get on one knee and tell me he loved me and offer me his ring in front of all of Freeport like daddy did with you.”<br>
<br>
“And Lucan would not do this with you?” Sylver asked.  “All the people in town are predicting he will be my son-in-law with the way he follows you around.”<br>
<br>
“More like stalks me.” Camille said, producing yet another frown from Sylver.  “I doubt Lucan understands what the word love means, would definitely NOT get on his knees in front of anyone for anything and the only ring he would give me is a collar around my neck.”<br>
<br>
“Then to hells with him.” Sylver nodded, and brought up his hand, murmuring something Camille could not understand.  A small red ring appeared from nowhere in his cupped palm.  He then took his daughter’s hand lightly, and fell with a groan to his knees.  “I love you Camille!” he announced to his bemused daughter and smiling wife, and placed the ring on Camille’s finger.  “There.” he said, standing as his knees popped.  “Happy now?”<br>
<br>
“Daddy,” Camille said, shaking her head at her father with a smile.  “I didn’t mean a levitation ring!”<br>
<br>
“Don’t knock it honey,” Emaus said.  “That was my engagement ring until your father found a camp he could farm for a real one.”<br>
<br>
“Speaking of camping,” Sylver said, kissing his daughter’s cheek and then another peck on his wife’s lips.  “I need to get to work or it will be summoned food and water tonight for dinner.”<br>
<br>
“Are you still going to thank Riverdane?” Camille asked.<br>
<br>
“He had better.” Emaus said warningly.<br>
<br>
“Yes, dear.” Sylver sighed, addressing both of them.  “I will go there now.  Pet, follow me.”  And opening the door to let out something Camille couldn’t see, her father left the house.<br>
<br>
“He certainly is handsome.” Emaus remarked.<br>
<br>
“Daddy?” Camille said, wrinkling her nose.  “He’s charming, but…”<br>
<br>
“Not your father, silly girl.” Emaus chuckled.  “Although I like the way Sylver’s eyebrows join like that over his nose.  Very….sexy when he scowls.”<br>
<br>
“Ewww, mother.” Camille laughed.  “Then who is handsome?  Lucan?”<br>
<br>
“Riverdane.” Emaus said.<br>
<br>
“Yes.” Camille sighed.  “His hair is prettier than mine, and his eyes…”<br>
<br>
“Although, he really should decide if he is going to grow that moustache or shave it off.” her mother said, nodding.<br>
<br>
“Yes!” Camille laughed, and then looked at her mother oddly.  “You’ve seen him then, recently?”<br>
<br>
“Yes.” her mother said.  “Coffee?”  And walked into the kitchen, leaving Camille standing with her mouth open.<br>
<br>
“Mother!” she cried, running into the kitchen after her.  “Where did you see him?  I have looked for him on the streets every day since that night in Ro…”<br>
<br>
“Oh, outside the house this morning, while you were sleeping.” Emaus said non-chalantly.  “Milk, sugar?”<br>
<br>
“He was HERE?” Camille exclaimed.<br>
<br>
“Yes,” Emaus said, feigning indifference.  “I went out to water the plants and he was aimlessly wandering around outside the house on the street.  He looked guilty I had  spotted him.  He explained he didn’t want to wake everyone up so could I please give a letter to Miss Stun, and then he hurried off.”  She raised her eyebrow archly at Camille.  “Not knowing who Miss Stun was, I simply said yes and put it in my apron.”<br>
<br>
“Me, mother!” Camille said, not sure why her heart was beating so quickly, and not caring.  “I’m Miss Stun!”<br>
<br>
“Oh, Camille,” her mother sighed.  “I hope THAT’S not the surname you chose…”<br>
<br>
“Mother!” Camille cried.  “Where is the letter??”<br>
<br>
“Oh, the letter.” Emaus remarked casually.  “I think your father’s pet just took it out with the trash…”<br>
<br>
“What??” Camille cried, starting to the door. Emaus’ laugh stopped her, and she turned to her mother.  There she was, standing in the doorway to the kitchen, fanning herself with an envelope.<br>
<br>
“Awfully warm in here suddenly, don’t you think?” Emaus chuckled, and then extended the envelope to Camille.<br>
<br>
The outside said simply, in blocky print, “Miss Stun”.  And inside, after she tore it open, was the phrases: Please meet me at the lake in West Commons late afternoon at five.  Bring your shield and sword.  We’ll spar.  River.<br>
<br>
“I won’t be in for dinner, tonight, mother.” Camille said, reading and re-reading the note.<br>
<br>
“I’ll tell your father you are with your girlfriends.” Emaus nodded sagely.<br>
<br>
“I don’t have any girlfriends, mother.”<br>
<br>
“I’ll make some up.  Your father will be ecstatic.  ” Emaus announced, eyes sparkling.<br>
<br>
“Thank you!” Camille exclaimed, hugging her mother tightly, letter still in her hand.<br>
<br>
“Ah youth.” Emaus commented with a smile, turning back to her coffee, as her daughter ran into her room, closing the door behind her.<br>
 <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.lby3.com/eq/leopa/misc/riverdane_animatedbanner.gif" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=riverdane>Riverdane</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 413<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(7/18/03 12:53 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=55.topic&index=45>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Wake (Mithaniel's Handmaiden, Breathe III)</span><hr size=1> She awoke to a hand stroking her cheek.  Her eyes flew open.<br>
<br>
Sylver removed his hand from her face.  His eyes were striken.<br>
<br>
“I’m sorry.” he said miserably.  “I didn’t mean what I said.  River was a good man.  I’m just so frightened for you…” And then he stopped, words failing him, and just sat at the edge of her bed, hands twisted in his lap, shaking.<br>
<br>
“I’m frightened too, Daddy.” she said softly, saddened to see her father reduced to this trembling old man.<br>
<br>
“I guess I should be thrilled.” he said, “My little girl, savior of the world.”<br>
<br>
“I’m not a little girl anymore, Daddy.” she said, holding his hands in hers, trying to steady them.<br>
<br>
“Aye, you’re a woman.” he agreed sadly, then attempted a weak smile.  “But not too old  to still call me Daddy.”<br>
<br>
“No,” she agreed, smiling back at him.  “Never that old.”<br>
<br>
“When do you leave?” he asked, smile fading as quickly as it had come.<br>
<br>
“Immediately.” she said, sitting up and swinging her legs off of the bed.  “What time is it?”<br>
<br>
“Noon.” he told her.  “We let you sleep while your mother proceeded to point out the many ways I am an ass.”<br>
<br>
“You’re just worried, Daddy.” she comforted him.  “And I love you for that.”<br>
<br>
“I love you too, precious.” he said, hugging her tight as they sat on the bed.  “I love you too.”<br>
<br>
They stayed embraced for a long time, neither saying a word, and then Sylver broke first, standing up.<br>
<br>
“You need to go, or I won’t let you leave.” he said.  “Say goodbye to your mother, save the world, and then make sure this time it doesn’t take you another year to come home for supper.”<br>
<br>
“I promise.” she said, kissing him on the cheek.  She left him sitting on the bed and went into the kitchen.  Her mother was sitting in front of yet another cup of coffee.  Her eyes lit up when she saw Camille.<br>
<br>
“Did your father…?” Emaus began.<br>
<br>
“Yes.” Camille answered before she could finish.  “It’s ok now.”<br>
<br>
“He loves you very much, Camille.” Emaus said with a sigh.  “We both do.  He never forgot how you used to sit on his knee laughing while his pets ran around the house.  You will always be that happy little girl to him.”<br>
<br>
“Sometimes I wish we had never grown old, mother.” Camille said.<br>
<br>
Emaus absently ran her hand through her own graying hair.  “So do I, Miss Stun.  So do I.”  Then she pointed to the pot on the stove.  “Coffee before you go?”<br>
<br>
“No, mother, I need to go.” Camille apologized.  “Every moment lost is a moment Grieg gets closer to finishing his machine.  I am afraid to close my eyes for fear I will sleep while River is destroyed, and then….all of us.”<br>
<br>
“I understand.” Emaus nodded.  “Do what you have to do.”<br>
<br>
They hugged, and Emaus planted a kiss on her daughter’s forehead.  “Come back to us soon.” she whispered.<br>
<br>
“I will.” Camille promised again, hoping she was speaking the truth.<br>
<br>
“Did she leave yet??” Sylver said suddenly, bursting into the room in a panic.  The women broke their embrace, as relief flooded the old man’s face.  In his hand was a small golden rod with a round ball at the end.  Set into the face of the sphere was a red button.<br>
<br>
“Ah, good, I thought I may have missed you.”  Sylver said, handing Camille the rod.  “Just in case, take this.”<br>
<br>
“What is it?” Camille asked curiously.   She had often seen clerics and casters with them strapped to their sides, but had always written them off as “non-melee” and never bothered to inquire.<br>
<br>
“What is it?” Sylver cried in surprise, wounded.  “It’s one of the only things that used to make me raid worthy, in the old days!”<br>
<br>
“It’s a modulation rod.  It’s why I married him.” Emaus said, nodding with a wicked grin.  “I love his rod.”<br>
<br>
“Mother!” Camille exclaimed.<br>
<br>
“Not in front of the child!” Sylver reprimanded her, eyes smiling above his exaggerated scowl.  His eyebrows met and became one.  In that moment, for a brief second, she understood what her mother found attractive in the old man, and it had nothing to do with his rod.<br>
<br>
“What does it do?” Camille asked.<br>
<br>
“See this button?” Sylver said, indicating it.  Camille nodded.  “When very low on mana, press it.  And steel yourself.  It does a dangerous amount of damage to your body, but converts the damage done into pure mana.  Only useable once, and only in emergencies.  Without care you could kill yourself with this,  but handled responsibly, well, let’s just say it has gotten your mother and I out of more than one bad situation.”<br>
<br>
“Thank you, Daddy.” she said, putting it carefully into her pack.<br>
<br>
“This way, I’m with you when you’re out there, in some way.” he said.<br>
<br>
“You’re both with me, always.” Camille said.<br>
<br>
“Go go.” Sylver said, opening the door.  “Before I have your mother root you.”<br>
<br>
“I’m going.” she said, laughing, “Sheesh, you’d think you were trying to get rid of me!”<br>
<br>
“Go.” he said quietly.<br>
<br>
She ran to him one final time, quickly hugging him, and left the house.  She glanced back only once, to see her parents standing in the doorway, arms around each others’ waists.<br>
Her father waved once, and even from the street, she could see the tears in his eyes.  She waved back, heart heavy, and started off for the guildhouse.<br>
<br>
She never saw her father alive again.<br>
