<br>
“This is not going to be easy.” she murmured.<br>
<br>
“No.” Rocsalt agreed, counting the guards patrolling the front gate.  “Lucan controls that militia he created when the Knights tossed him, doesn’t he?”<br>
<br>
“Aye.” Camille confirmed, brow furrowed.  “The Freeport Militia outnumbers the Knights of Truth at least three to one.  It’s one of the reasons the Knights cannot take back control of the city.  But the Militia is mainly hired thugs, not like the trained Knights of Truth.  The fact that they don’t oust Lucan and his mercenaries amazes me.  It’s one of the reasons I’m glad River took me away from all of that with Razor’s Edge.  If I had stayed on with the Knights, I don’t think I could have dealt with becoming the weak force they have become.  All because of politics.  Back in the day, Freeport was a poor city.  The Knights imposed extremely low taxes, and protected it as best they could from outside enemies who would take it over.  But then Neriak grew bolder, and Dervs fell in with them, and we found ourselves needing more money, more troops.  So Lucan proposed higher taxes, a toll on the road leading to Rivervale, bringing in non-Knights to pick up the slack on defenses.  He had a solid supporter in Sir Bamible, one of the Knights’ High Council.  And for a while, it seemed to work.  The teir’dal invasions slowed, the city coffers grew fat, the Derv ambushes halted.  What did it matter that shopkeepers were paying three times the taxes, that you couldn’t walk to go fish in the Lake in West Commons without paying a toll, that criminals that you saw locked up the week before were walking the streets drunk swinging swords in the name of being the ‘new police’ of Freeport?  Dane, River’s father, was probably the most vocal in opposition to Lucan’s increasing power.  ‘He’s turning us into a human version of Neriak.’ was his argument, after Lucan’s thugs beat a man to death after showing mild opposition to the latest tax hike.  Beat to death, not for not paying the taxes, but for questioning them.  Lucan claimed the man pulled a knife on two of his tax collectors and had to be restrained, fought back violently, and was killed in the ensuing battle.  But River and I both knew Frebalin.  He wouldn’t have raised a knife to his own steak.  So, Dane was respected enough to be listened to, and an investigation began.  Before it could come up with any hard evidence tho, Lucan renounced the Knights as a ‘weak puppet force following an archaic code that would die with the old men (Dane and supporters) who believed in it.  Dane called mutiny, Lucan shouted impotence, and it was a race to see who could act first, the Knights kicking Lucan out, or Lucan quitting.  Lucan left, with his childhood friend, the cleric Brother Jentry from the Temple of Marr.  Lucan still had his men, and upon closer look, one could tell that there were far more of them than the Knights; inclusion into the Knights of Truth required you were a paladin, and that required the ability to learn to Lay on Hands, but to be part of Lucan’s mob all you needed to do was to be willing to kill when Lucan commanded it.  In a move anticipated by Dane, Lucan kept his men in place, renaming them the Freeport Militia and declaring them the new government of Freeport.  The people were confused with who to follow, but fear often is a more powerful inducement than honor, and they bowed under Lucan’s will.  My father-in-law had intended to bring in the Qeynos Guard to help remove Lucan’s foothold in Freeport, but Qeynos had its own problems at the time with corruption spreading through their own ranks.  And before Dane could arrange to ally with Qeynos, well, you know,  that sand giant in Oasis…”<br>
<br>
Talvarien looked down in the sand.  “That almost destroyed River.”<br>
<br>
“Aye.” Camille said.  “I don’t think Dane knew what he was up against when he tried to route Cazel out of power in North Oasis.  Dane had handled sand giants single handledly before, but their new leader was a lot stronger than any of us realized.”<br>
<br>
“Not too strong for a pissed off Razor’s Edge.” Rocsalt reminded her, the memory fresh in his eyes.<br>
<br>
“Aye.” Camille remembered.  “And thank gods you guys tailed River.  He would have followed his father into the grave, the way he flew out of the house.”<br>
<br>
“Should have taken out Lucan after, but I don’t think any of us realized…” Rocsalt said.<br>
<br>
“No.” Camille agreed.  “River wouldn’t involve himself in his father’s mission, knowing full well the Knights wouldn’t have followed him, or me.  River was, to quote Sir Bamible, ‘the son of a mad woman and a demon-god.’ and I was the woman who disgraced the Knights and married him.  Had River pushed Dane’s fight, he would have ended up tearing out his hair in frustration.  So, Freeport fell under the power of Lucan and his Militia, and the Knights were allowed, ALLOWED, to continue their training as long as they did not interfere in North Freeport.  Sir Bamible readily agreed, and…well, you see what a joke the Knights have become.”<br>
<br>
“Wow.” Talvarien remarked.  “I knew the town had gone to pot, but I didn’t know the details.”<br>
<br>
“That’s the problem.” Camille said, eyes hard as she stared at the Freeport Militia flanking the walls.  “People just accept, instead of doing things to change things.”<br>
<br>
“So, next?” Grelin said.<br>
<br>
“Next?” Camille asked.  “We have an army of vampires in Befallen ready to attack the town tonight, and I have no idea if they will strike without Mistmoore, but my family is in there, and I don’t intend to find out.  And I have to figure out how to get that stolen pommel from Lucan.  You guys head back to the guildhouse.  Invis CloudDancer if you would; I’d prefer the fewer eyes to see her in this city, the better.”  The unicorn tossed her head, agitated.  She stroked CloudDancer’s flank and whispered in her ear to follow the men.  Then she looked back out toward the city.<br>
<br>
“And me?” she finished.  “I’m going to run a fool’s errand and see if the Knights of Truth are interested in hearing how their city is run by a man who is in league with Innoruuk.”<br>
 <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.lby3.com/eq/leopa/misc/riverdane_animatedbanner.gif" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=riverdane>Riverdane</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 428<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(7/24/03 12:53 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=55.topic&index=59>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Wake (Mithaniel's Handmaiden, Breathe III)</span><hr size=1> “Vampires are in Befallen?” Thoren Rolius asked. <br>
<br>
“Were.” Camille corrected.  “I don’t know if they are there now, with Mistmoore’s demise, but I don’t think we should chance that.”<br>
<br>
“Mistmoore’s demise.” Sir Bamible repeated, stroking his grey beard.  The oldest of the five members of the High Council, he had been the only one of the Council not to greet her warmly when she requested audience.  And his cool tone suggested that he did not believe a word of what she had told them.  <br>
<br>
“Let me see if I have this correct.” Bamible said, getting up and pacing behind the long table the Council was seated at.  “You go to Castle Mistmoore, on some quest, to recover a hilt and pommel from the vampire lord himself…”<br>
<br>
“Not some quest.” Camille said carefully.  “A quest from Marr.”<br>
<br>
“Ah yes!” Bamible laughed shortly.  “From our god Himself.  A quest you have requested not to be questioned about.  Anyway, you go to Castle Mistmoore, and with four people destroy a being that is more myth than reality.  While there, he discloses to you that part of your quest now lies in the hand of the evil Lucan D’lere, who has turned away from the good of humankind and now serves Innoruuk.  Not only do you want us to march our men into Befallen to slay these vampire, but you want us to put Lucan, the leader of the Freeport Milita, into custody for demon-worship, and turn over this pommel to you.”<br>
<br>
“Yes.” Camille said tightly, meeting his mocking gaze steadily.<br>
<br>
“Camille,” Theron hedged, not looking at her, “This all sounds so…”<br>
<br>
“Preposterous!” Bamible finished loudly.  Theron scowled; he did not like having words, especially ones he would not have used, placed in his mouth by the older knight, but even within the Council, Bamible was his superior, by sheer years served.<br>
<br>
“Lucan D’Lere’s ways may not be to our liking,” Bamible continued, glancing at his fellow Council members quickly, “But it does keep the peace in Freeport, and the city has never been richer than it is now.  We are no Qeynos; we have the Dervs to the south of us, the dark elves to the northeast and our closest ‘allies’, if you can say that of those foolish halflings, are separated by a forest they are afraid to enter by night.  We used to sit here behind our paper walls with our throats exposed, begging to be cut.  Through Lucan’s work we have become a stronghold, and have not suffered a skirmish with our unfriendly neighbors since!”<br>
<br>
“Enough, please, of making a hero of that egomaniac…” Theron cut in, anger in his voice.<br>
<br>
“Regardless,” Bamible continued, “Egomaniac or not, Lucan D’lere has kept Freeport just that…free.  Now in comes one of our prodigal daughters, with fantastic stories of vampires, secret quests, and demonic alliances, and asks us to attempt to overthrow the very guards that are keeping us safe…”<br>
<br>
“WE used to keep us safe.” Camille said through clenched teeth.<br>
<br>
“There is no ‘we’, Ms. Wyldechylde.” Bamible said, looking down his nose at her.  “There was no ‘we’ the moment you fell in with the son of the very demon you claim Lucan is involved with.”  He turned away from her at that point, as if she didn’t exist.  “It is my suggestion, gentleman, that we ask the Militia to investigate Befallen, if anything to quell the growing concern I see in your eyes over this woman’s monster stories.  As to Lucan and this pommel, if it exists at all, then I imagine her desire for it and him having it is the basis for this little attempt at character assassination, and to put no more stock in it than that.”<br>
<br>
Camille looked at the faces of the other four men.  Theron was watching them as well, his eyes darting from one to the other.  But the other three, unwilling to provoke Bamible, the oldest of them, just nodded.<br>
<br>
“Then we are agreed?” Bamible said, as Camille stared with no surprise at the three men, no, SHEEP, she corrected, as they verbally said they did.<br>
<br>
“Opposed.” Theron said, knowing it was pointless, but saying it anyway.<br>
<br>
“Noted.” Bamible replied.  “Then the plan is to have the Militia dispatched to Befallen and the rest of the charges dismissed.”  He began striding to the exit.  “If you gentlemen will excuse me, I will ask Lucan to head to West Commons with his men.  Good day.”  And with that he exited.  The other three Council members mumbled goodbye, unable to look at her as they passed, leaving her alone with Theron.<br>
<br>
“Camille…” Theron began apologetically.<br>
<br>
“What happened to us, Theron?” Camille asked, face hot.  “When did we stop seeking the truth and allowed ourselves to be led by lies?”  Behind the table, the statue of Mithaniel looked down upon them with sightless eyes, his Sword of Truth lifted high.<br>
<br>
“I don’t know.” Theron half whispered, gaze dropping from under her firey glare.  It was a long pause before he could look up again.<br>
<br>
When he did, she was gone.<br>
 <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.lby3.com/eq/leopa/misc/riverdane_animatedbanner.gif" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=riverdane>Riverdane</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 429<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(7/24/03 2:32 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=55.topic&index=60>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Wake (Mithaniel's Handmaiden, Breathe III)</span><hr size=1> Camille marched furiously through the front entrance of the Halls of Truth into the street.  Tears of frustration fought their way up to her eyes, but she blinked them back.  Knights don’t cry, godsdamit!<br>
<br>
“Cami, wait!” she heard Theron call from behind her, but she ignored him, marching toward the guildhouse.<br>
<br>
“Cami!” he called again.  And then, as if gripped by invisible bonds, she felt her progress halt dead in its tracks.  She struggled to take a step forward, but his root held fast, and she turned agrily to face him.<br>
<br>
The look on her face stopped him as if she had rooted him herself.<br>
<br>
“Release me.” she said dangerously.  “I never want to step foot on this soil again.”<br>
<br>
“Camille…” Theron began, trying to calm the look of rage.<br>
<br>
“RELEASE ME.” she ordered.<br>
<br>
“It’s root…” he apologized.  “I…can’t.”<br>
<br>
She suddenly felt foolish.  She knew that.  Bamible’s mock-hearing had thrown her off so badly she was forgetting the basics.  She stopped struggling with Theron’s spell and took a deep breath.<br>
<br>
“What do you want?” she asked evenly.<br>
<br>
“I thought…” Theron began, and then stopped, as Camille’s body stumbled forward, the root spell dissipating.  He did not recast.  Just waited for her to storm away.<br>
<br>
She didn’t.<br>
<br>
“What do you want?” she repeated.<br>
<br>
“I want to know the truth.” he said simply.  “Come with me to Befallen.  I don’t trust Lucan or his men.  Someone should be there to ascertain what is really in there.”<br>
<br>
Camille stared at him for a moment, and then nodded shortly.  She turned away from him and started walking, waiting for him to fall in place beside her.  Instead, he stepped directly in front of her, stopping her in her stride.  She looked up into his eyes, an impatient query in them.<br>
<br>
“I just want you to understand.” Theron said quietly, meeting her eyes directly.  “Not all of the Knights are cowards.  Some of us didn’t move on to the military guilds or the family guilds because we believed in the Knights, and wanted to continue on with what we began as children.  And some of us, after all the garbage that has been thrown at us, the shame, the lies, STILL believe.  So, for the love of Marr, remember what we learned together, and that we once stood for something higher than all of us.  If River had not taken you with him, you would still be one of us, growing sick as one by one the codes by which we were knighted became compromised by the very men who taught them to us.  We are not all Sir Bamibles, or Lucans.  Some of us are still Knights.  We have just lost sight of the truth.”<br>
<br>
Camille’s face softened, and she nodded again, this time in forgiveness.<br>
<br>
“Let’s go.” Theron said. <br>
